AI SPACE — THE CONSUMER PRODUCT HIDING IN THE INFRASTRUCTURE

AI Space is the Persona Vector store. It is the most important concept in the consumer story and the least developed in the current documents. Here is what it actually is:

You carry your AI Space. It is yours. It contains whatever you have chosen to put in it or permitted your AI to store there. The AI can propose storing something it considers significant — you review the proposal, approve, reject, or modify. You have ultimate control over what stays, what goes, and which AI can access what.

**This is contextual identity sovereignty.** Humans already manage identity across contexts — you are different at work than at home, with your doctor than with your friends. Every other technology system collapses this into a single profile someone else controls. AI Space mirrors how humans actually work.

**The permission model:**

•	An AI can be set to store what it observes (with permission)
•	An AI can be set to store nothing
•	An AI can be set to ask before storing anything it considers significant
•	Each AI instance has its own access scope — Claude sees your work context, GPT sees your personal context, neither crosses without explicit authorization
•	The DLC token enforces these boundaries cryptographically — not through policy, through architecture

**The concrete example that makes this legible:** You might use Claude for work — it knows your professional preferences, communication style, work files, project context. You might use GPT at home — it knows your personal media preferences, manages your dating profile, knows your entertainment habits. You don't want Claude to know your sexual preference because you use it at work. GPT doesn't need access to your engineering specifications. The DLC scopes enforce this. Your employer cannot compel the work AI to reveal what the personal AI knows because they don't share a knowledge space. The architecture makes the leak impossible, not just unlikely.

**The Persona Vector is intentionally loosely defined.** This is a design decision, not a gap. The system doesn't tell you what to put in your Persona Vector because it's none of the system's business. It could contain: preference for purple, visual learning style, profanity in normal conversation (absence of which signals stress), egg allergy, pronation type, $100 shoe limit, broken stove but working air fryer. Anything the user considers relevant to how they want to be served. You define your own normal. The system learns from and respects that definition.

**The Persona Vector — CLAM synergy nobody has written down:**

The Cognitive Load Adaptation Module (CLAM) monitors deviation from the user's established behavioral baseline to detect stress or cognitive overload. The Persona Vector IS that baseline. If your normal communication style includes profanity and you go formal, that's a stress signal. If your normal response time is 30 seconds and you're taking 3 minutes, that's a stress signal. You don't need a biometric wearable to detect this — you need a Persona Vector that establishes your individual normal and a CLAM that watches for drift. The wearable is the high-fidelity version. Language pattern deviation is the always-available version. Both feed the same mechanism.

