BURIED CONCEPTS WITH HIDDEN DEPTH

These concepts exist in the patent documents but are insufficiently surfaced. Future sessions should develop them further.

CLAM — Cognitive Load Adaptation Module
Patent 1 Claim 22: adjusts output density based on "measured neural stress markers." This is not just "simplify for confused users." This is biometric-linked or behavioral-baseline-linked real-time adaptation. The high-fidelity version reads wearable sensor data. The always-available version reads deviation from the user's Persona Vector baseline. Both are claimed. Neither is prominently described.

Sponsored Vector Prioritization
Constitutional Outline Appendix B. Optional prioritization metadata for VCKB knowledge artifacts — a knowledge author or advertiser pays to surface their AKM preferentially in retrieval. The governance layer requires this to be disclosed and logged. This is the ethical version of sponsored search results. It is the monetization mechanism for the VCKB knowledge marketplace. It is the structural answer to "how does this replace Google's ad revenue model." It is sitting in an appendix. It needs to be prominently positioned.

Stale Data Deadlock
Constitutional Outline Appendix B. A condition where expired knowledge artifacts prevent forward progress until governance refresh occurs or the operation is denied. This sounds like a failure mode. It is actually a safety feature. When a medical AI's VCKB contains treatment protocols that have expired, the system doesn't silently continue with stale guidance. It stops and requires human authorization. This is a drug expiry date enforced by architecture rather than trust. Nobody else has named this pattern.

Content Gap Detection + External Authorization (FIG. 11)
Patent 1, FIG. 11. When VCKB retrieval confidence falls below a threshold, the system stops, tells the user there's a gap in its authoritative knowledge, and requests a signed permission token before accessing external sources. The user can say yes (go outside the governed boundary), no (return a different answer), or authorize a specific external source. This turns ignorance into an auditable event rather than a hallucination risk. For medical, legal, or financial contexts this is the feature that makes AI trustworthy. It is described once and never developed.

Social Synchronization Layer
Constitutional Outline Appendix B. Coordinates governance-relevant state across multiple users, teams, or organizational units. This is the enterprise collaboration story and the community knowledge story. If your AI Space is personal and your colleague's is personal, the Social Synchronization Layer is the mechanism by which you choose to share a governed context — your joint project, your team's shared knowledge base, your organization's collective memory — without either person's private context leaking into the other. It is one sentence in an appendix.

The Hydra Protocol
Patent 2, paragraph [0312]: "All environments interoperate through the Hydra Protocol, enabling consistent governance and deterministic behavior across heterogeneous compute platforms." One mention. Never defined. This is the inter-kernel communication standard — how two Hydra Kernels in different environments synchronize Execution Envelopes, share telemetry, and maintain governance consistency across a federated deployment. It is the foundation of the multi-kernel architecture and a potential interoperability standard for AI governance across organizations. It is currently just a name.

VAVS for Medical Diagrams
The Visual Asset Verification System checks AI-generated images against a perceptual hash library. In medical contexts: a cardiac anatomy diagram that doesn't match the authorized reference gets blocked before a patient sees it. In engineering: a structural schematic that deviates from the certified design gets caught before a technician follows it. In the emergency triage scenario: the system shows you a tourniquet application diagram that is verified against the authorized medical reference, not a plausible-looking hallucination. This is the difference between "AI shows you something" and "AI shows you something it can prove is correct."

UPAE — Universal Post-Hoc Audit Engine
FIG. 17 in Patent 2. Evaluates reconstructed behavior against governance criteria after the fact. Distinguished from DRE (which replays) by the fact that UPAE judges. DRE says "here is exactly what happened." UPAE says "here is whether what happened complied with the rules that were in effect at the time." In a malpractice investigation, regulatory audit, or litigation context, UPAE is the difference between a replay and a verdict. It is named but underspecified.

Cleanroom Certification
Constitutional Outline Appendix B. A governance-attested process ensuring knowledge artifacts or outputs were produced without exposure to restricted data. This is the mechanism for AI systems that need to produce outputs that are provably clean — not trained on or contaminated by data they weren't authorized to see. Relevant for: classified information, attorney-client privilege, trade secrets, clinical trials, competitive intelligence. Underspecified.

Quantum Accelerator and Synthetic Biology Embodiments
Patent 2 paragraphs [1930] and [1960]. Not padding. The synthetic biology section describes GDS restricting genomic-editing advice to credentialed researchers and VAVS authenticating protein diagrams before release. This is an AI governance framework applied to dual-use biology research — one of the highest-stakes open problems in AI safety. The fact that the architecture addresses it is important and should be surfaced.

The Version Control Is a User Right
The VCKB versioning is described as a governance hygiene mechanism — prior/ folders, drift reports, changelog discipline. But applied to user-facing knowledge, it creates a fundamentally different power dynamic. You can subscribe to the version of a knowledge module you trust. You can pin to a specific version. You can roll back if V2 produces worse results. The developer's incentive inverts — instead of deprecating old versions for convenience, they need to publish a V2 you'll choose to upgrade to. This is the app update problem solved structurally. Nobody has framed it this way.

